{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}} {{Infobox museum | name = American Oriental Society | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = AOSmedallion1.png | imagesize = 200px | caption = American Oriental Society medallion | map_type = | map_caption = | map_alt = | coordinates = | established = September 7, 1842 | dissolved = | location = | type = Learned society | collection = | visitors = | director = | president = | curator = | publictransit = | network = | website = [http://www.umich.edu/~aos/ umich.edu/~aos/] }} The '''American Oriental Society''' was chartered under the laws of [[Commonwealth of Massachusetts|Massachusetts]] on September 7, 1842. It is one of the oldest [[learned society|learned societies]] in [[United States|America]],<ref name=ASU>{{cite web|title=ASU professor named president of American Oriental Society|url=https://asunow.asu.edu/content/asu-professor-named-president-american-oriental-society|website=ASU Now|date=April 8, 2011}}</ref> and is the oldest devoted to a particular field of scholarship.<ref>{{cite web|title=American Oriental Society|url=http://www.acls.org/societies/societies.aspx?sid=50895c50-c9a2-db11-a735-000c2903e717|publisher=ACLS|accessdate=December 21, 2011}}</ref>
It is closely associated with [[Yale University]], which is the site of its library. The society publishes a journal quarterly, the ''[[Journal of the American Oriental Society]]'', the most important American serial publication in the historical languages of Asia. Former presidents include [[Theodore Dwight Woolsey]],<ref name=ASU/> [[James Hadley (scholar)|James Hadley]],<ref name=ASU/> [[William Dwight Whitney]],<ref name=ASU/> [[Daniel Coit Gilman|Daniel C. Gilman]],<ref name=ASU/> [[William Hayes Ward|William H. Ward]], [[Crawford Howell Toy|Crawford H. Toy]], [[Morris Jastrow, Jr.]], [[Harold H. Bender]] and [[Ludo Rocher]].
