{{Infobox military installation | name = Marsa Battery | native_name = Batterija tal-Marsa | partof = the [[Fortifications of Malta#French occupation (1798–1800)|French blockade batteries]] | location = [[Marsa, Malta|Marsa]], [[Malta]] | image = [[File:Fortifications Interpretation Centre (Valletta) 15.jpg|300px]] | caption = Reconstruction of Marsa Battery by [[Stephen C. Spiteri]] at the [[Fortifications Interpretation Centre]] | map = Jesuit Hill & Marsa Batteries map.png | image_mapsize = 300px | map_caption = Map of Marsa Battery and [[Jesuit Hill Battery]] | type = [[Artillery battery]] | coordinates = {{coord|35|52|54.1|N|14|30|02.6|E|type:landmark_region:MT|display=inline}} | built = {{circa}} 1798 | used = {{circa}} 1798–1800 | builder = [[Maltese people|Maltese]] insurgents | materials = [[Limestone]] | fate = Demolished | battles = [[Siege of Malta (1798–1800)]] }}
'''Marsa Battery''' ({{lang-mt|Batterija tal-Marsa}}) was an [[artillery battery]] in [[Marsa, Malta|Marsa]], [[Malta]], built by Maltese insurgents during the [[Siege of Malta (1798–1800)|French blockade]] of 1798-1800. It was part of [[Fortifications of Malta#French occupation (1798–1800)|a chain of batteries, redoubts and entrenchments]] encircling the French positions in [[Marsamxett Harbour|Marsamxett]] and the [[Grand Harbour]].
The battery was built at the bottom of Jesuit Hill, close to the shoreline. [[Jesuit Hill Battery]] was located nearby on higher ground. The battery was small, and consisted of a small masonry parapet with three embrasures, a hardstone gun platform, a sentry room on the left, and a flanking rubble wall on the right. A magazine was also built to the rear of the battery. Marsa Battery was designed by Salvatore Camilleri from [[Valletta]].
Like the other French blockade fortifications, Marsa Battery was dismantled, possibly sometime after 1814. No traces of the battery can be seen today, and the area is now heavily industrialized. The site of the battery is now occupied by the [[Marsa Power Station]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Spiteri|first1=Stephen C.|title=Maltese ‘siege’ batteries of the blockade 1798-1800|journal=Arx - Online Journal of Military Architecture and Fortification|date=May 2008|issue=6|page=37|url=http://www.militaryarchitecture.com/images/stories/Arx/arx6-2008.pdf|accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref>
