{{italic title}}
[[File:McDonaldization.jpeg|thumb|The McDonaldization of Society: 20th Anniversary Edition cover art]]
'''''The McDonaldization of Society''''' is a 1993 [[book]] by [[sociologist]] [[George Ritzer]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Warner|first1=Malcolm|title=The McDonaldization of Society (book review)|journal=Journal of General Management|date=1 December 1993|volume=19|issue=2|pages=86-90|doi=10.1177/030630709301900207|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/030630709301900207?journalCode=gema|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref> Ritzer suggests that in the later part of the 20th century the socially-structured form of the [[fast-food restaurant]] has become the organizational force representing and extending the process of rationalization into the realm of everyday interaction and individual identity. [[McDonald's]] of the 1990s serves as the case model.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The McDonaldization of society, 6th ed|journal=Reference & Research Book News|date=August 2010|volume=25|issue=3|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+McDonaldization+of+society%2C+6th+ed-a0233054480|accessdate=2 January 2018|publisher=The Free Library}}</ref> The book introduced the term [[McDonaldization]] to learned discourse as a way to describe a social process which produces "mind-numbing sameness", according to a 2002 review of a related academic text.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gilbert|first1=Elllen D|title=Review: Fast Food, Fast Track: Immigrants, Big Business, and the American Dream|journal=Library Journal|date=15 April 2002|volume=127|issue=7|page=112|url=https://bepl.ent.sirsi.net/client/en_US/default/search/detailnonmodal/ent:$002f$002fSD_ILS$002f0$002fSD_ILS:1168840/ada|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref>

In ''McDonaldization'' Ritzer expands and updates central elements from the work of [[Max Weber]] and produces a critical analysis of the impact of social-structural change on human interaction and identity. The central theme in Weber's analysis of modern society was the process of [[Rationalization (sociology)|rationalization]]; a far-reaching process whereby traditional modes of thinking were replaced by an ends/means analysis concerned with efficiency and formalized [[social control]]. Weber argued that the [[Archetype|archetypal]] manifestation of this process was the [[bureaucracy]]; a large, formal organization characterized by a hierarchical authority structure, well-established [[Division of labour|division of labor]], written rules and regulations, impersonality and a concern for technical competence. Bureaucratic organizations not only represent the process of rationalization, the structure they impose on human interaction and thinking furthers the process, leading to an increasingly rationalized world. The process affects all aspects of everyday life. 

